Pronunciation: 'fa-l&amp;-sE<br>
Function: noun<br>
Inflected Form(s): plural -cies<br>
Etymology: Latin fallacia, from fallac-, fallax deceitful, from fallere to deceive<br>
Date: 14th century<br>
1 a obsolete : GUILE, TRICKERY b : deceptive appearance : DECEPTION<br>
2 a : a false or mistaken idea &lt;popular fallacies&gt; b : erroneous character : ERRONEOUSNESS<br>
3 : an often plausible argument using false or invalid inference <br>
<br>
There is no such fallacy in standard logical debate known as “ridicule as an arguement”.  That is neither a plausible argument using false or invalid inferences, nor trickery.  It is pretty much a reflection of the respect you have shown being returned to you.<br>
<br>
There are several childish acts that can be performed in a debate, kudos to you for using so many of them.  However, this will not be a productive exchange of information if you remain incapable of agreeing on terms and language.  Not that you have demonstrated an interest in exchanging ideas, just spewing vitriol as fast as possible and tenaciously refusing anything that might threaten your fragile grip on Einstein’s coattails.  <br>
<br>
Now, as I have said repeatedly, I do not care if Einstein was a deist or an atheist or a worshipper of The Great Pumpkin. It makes no difference to me personally.  What does matter is when people try and validate their position by attaching it to someone else.  This is a logical fallacy known as the Argument from Authority.  The implication that because someone is smart or has notoriety or a degree, their statements are inherently more valid than the opposing opinions.  What compounds this failing is when they are incorrectly attributing a position to someone who doesn’t hold it!  Which is the case at hand where you michael are trying to repaint Einstein as a theist when he clearly and repeatedly declared he wasn’t in word, deed and print.<br>
<br>
I can look at a deist organization and read their charter and self-description, I can speak to deists and ask their views, they can come forward and tell you themselves what they think and feel, and it will never be enough for you because it doesn’t support your beliefs.  Ultimately, we can never roll out each and every single deist in the universe and scrutinize their minds to the utmost degree and absolutely, conclusively without doubt or hesitation say we know exactly specifically precisely what they are.  That is not possible.  How sad that that impossibility is where your ‘proof’ stands.<br>
<br>
I have no problem admitting when I am wrong, I have spent my life doing it.  The nice part is that the more often you see your mistakes and acknowledge them, the less often they arise again, because you learnt from them and grew from the experience.  You have been asked directly to explain your reasons for your belief, and yet have not.  You have been asked for specific studies and explanations, which you artfully turn into higher demands from the requestor rather than reasoned responses.  You like the interjectory and chaotic reply style that lacks cohesion and thought.  A collection of one-liner jabs, how admirable.<br>
<br>
Put up or shut up mike.  Lets hear the merit of your ‘experiences’ and see your beliefs.<br>
