&gt;&gt;... I submit that, if a person calls themselves a deist, but does not ascribe to these beliefs, they are not actually a deist, they are just calling themselves the wrong thing.)<br>
<br>
I didn't say that.  I said deism is a subset of &quot;theism&quot;, which is itself distinctly different from an atheist.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;Einstein said:  “I do not believe in a personal God and I have never denied this but have expressed it clearly.” See how this suggests he followed the deist ideology more than theist? <br>
<br>
I see your reasoning and your reasoning on that point seems sound.  I do not however agree with your assesment of the term &quot;theist&quot;.  Theism only requires that you believe in a creator, regardless of whether or not you believe you can experience God personally.<br>
 <br>
“Neither can I believe that the individual survives the death of his body, although feeble souls harbor such thoughts through fear or ridiculous egotisms” See the implications of your heaven idea?<br>
<br>
I don't believe what most folks think of their &quot;self identity&quot;, i.e. body, ego, belief systems, will survive physical death and the light of truth either, but I do believe we have &quot;souls&quot;.  Einstein also talked about souls and spirits quite often.  Why?<br>
<br>
“A man's ethical behavior should be based effectually on sympathy, education, and social ties and needs; no religious basis is necessary.” See how god DOESN’T enter into his decisions?<br>
<br>
Yes, it's the credo I live by.  Your point?<br>
<br>
“Spiritualism is for me no more than a symptom of weakness and confusion.” See how this reflects on his views?<br>
<br>
I suppose that depends on how you define the term &quot;spiritualism&quot; and what context this sentence was used in.  Do you have a reference for that one?<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;(when asked if he believed in immortality) “No, and one life is enough for me.”<br>
<br>
Ok.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;“In their struggle for the ethical good, teachers of religion must have the stature to give up the doctrine of a personal God” Again, the distancing of himself from theism.<br>
<br>
Distancing himself from religion, not God.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;“What I see in Nature is a magnificent structure that we can comprehend only very imperfectly, and that must fill a thinking person with a feeling of humility. This is a genuinely religious feeling that has nothing to do with mysticism.” This may clarify your misconception about hairsplitting and definitions. Certainly it speaks of what he felt was genuine feeling vs false mysticism. <br>
<br>
Of course he also said:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;The finest emotion of which we are capable is the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>mystic</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> emotion. Herein lies the germ of all art and all true science. Anyone to whom this feeling is alien, who is no longer capable of wonderment and lives in a state of fear is a dead man. To know that what is impenatrable for us really exists and manifests itself as the highest wisdom and the most radiant beauty, whose gross forms alone are intelligible to our poor faculties - this knowledge, this feeling ... that is the core of the true religious sentiment. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>In this sense, and in this sense alone, I rank myself amoung profoundly religious men.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->&quot; <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;As far as the studies go, I am not sure what you think our colleges were like in the late 1920’s and early 30’s but if I recall depression economics, those numbers probably reflect a substantial proportion of the campus. <br>
<br>
It's a pitiful study that didn't ask about theism vs. atheism, but only &quot;devotely religious&quot; vs. &quot;atheistic tendencies&quot; which leads to all kinds of interpretations as to meaning.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;All that aside, if you wish to refute the study, please roll out a study that shows other data or better diligence.<br>
<br>
I've yet to see anything to worth bothering to refute!  Why bother?<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;You can snear and deride (you do it so regularly) as much as you like, but you haven’t refuted it.<br>
<br>
Why do I need bother refuting a link that doesn't even ask pertinatent questions related to her claims.  <br>
<br>
M&gt;&gt; I don't believe in the &quot;supernatural&quot; by the way.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;You have the most bizarre views of the world imaginable.<br>
<br>
How so?<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;You believe in god and heaven, but not the supernatural?<br>
<br>
No, I believe God is perfectly &quot;natural&quot;, in fact THE SINGLE MOST natural thing in creation.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;What exactly qualifies as supernatural in your world?<br>
<br>
I dunno.  I don't much believe in the concept to start with, and I certainly don't believe in anything &quot;supernatural&quot;!<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;Main Entry: su·per·nat·u·ral <br>
Pronunciation: &quot;sü-p&amp;r-'na-ch&amp;-r&amp;l, -'nach-r&amp;l<br>
Function: adjective<br>
Etymology: Medieval Latin supernaturalis, from Latin super- + natura nature<br>
Date: 15th century<br>
1 : of or relating to an order of existence beyond the visible observable universe; <br>
<br>
By this definition, atoms, electrons and neutrinos are &quot;supernatural&quot;.  I suppose maybe I do then believe in supernatural things afterall. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;especially : of or relating to God or a god, demigod, spirit, or devil<br>
<br>
Oh, so someone gets to decide that God is supernatural by their definition?  Does this mean that neutrino's are supernatural?  I've never seen one of those either.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;2 a : departing from what is usual or normal especially so as to appear to transcend the laws of nature b :<br>
<br>
I don't think God transends the laws of nature, though maybe it might &quot;appear&quot; that way.  Then again, a magnet floating above a superconductive plate &quot;appears&quot; to defy the laws of gravity too.  Is that a supernatural phenomenon too since it &quot;appears&quot; to defy the laws of gravity?<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;attributed to an invisible agent (as a ghost or spirit)<br>
<br>
You mean like neutrinos?<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;Here comes the ad hominem.....you are a freak and a loony.<br>
<br>
I just love it when your superior intellect gets rude and uptight.  Do me a favor. Go stand under the stars tonight and tell me that you KNOW WITH CERTAINTY that this gigantic universe wasn't created intentionally.  Then tell me how you know this scientifically.   Until you do, I'll just figure you're blowing smoke and stuck in your own pitiful little ego.  How that for an ad hom on my part? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> Michael</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#3333ff>(2/13/03 9:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=86.topic&index=60>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Einstein and Spirit, mind and God</span><hr size=1> &quot;Great spirits have always found violent opposition from mediocre minds. The latter cannot understand it when a man does not thoughtlessly submit to hereditary prejudices but honestly and courageously uses his intelligence.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;If the possibility of the spiritual development of all individuals is to be secured, a second kind of outward freedom is necessary. The development of science and of the creative activities of the spirit in general requires still another kind of freedom, which may be characterised as inward freedom. It is this freedom of the spirit which consists in the interdependence of thought from the restrictions of authoritarian and social prejudices as well as from unphilosophical routinizing and habit in general. This inward freedom is an infrequent gift of nature and a worthy object for the individual.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Only one who devotes himself to a cause with his whole strength and soul can be a true master. For this reason mastery demands all of a person.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;I maintain that cosmic religiousness is the strongest and most noble driving force of scientific research.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;The intuitive mind is a sacred gift and the rational mind is a faithful servant. We have created a society that honors the servant and has forgotten the gift.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;We should take care not to make the intellect our god; it has, of course, powerful muscles, but no personality.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Before God we are all equally wise - and equally foolish.&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top">  Page <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showMessageRange?topicID=86.topic&start=1&stop=20>1</a><a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showMessageRange?topicID=86.topic&start=21&stop=40>2</a> <b>3</b> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showMessageRange?topicID=86.topic&start=61&stop=80>4</a><a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showMessageRange?topicID=86.topic&start=81&stop=100>5</a><a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showMessageRange?topicID=86.topic&start=101&stop=120>6</a><a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showMessageRange?topicID=86.topic&start=121&stop=140>7</a><a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showMessageRange?topicID=86.topic&start=141&stop=141>8</a> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showPrevMessage?topicID=86.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showNextMessage?topicID=86.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=86.topic&index=60><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/bluesparty/addReply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.emailToFriend?topicID=86.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.threadControl?topicID=86.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/bluesparty/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Contr